      "bodyTr": "Foreign visitors to South Korea surpassed all previous quarterly records in the first quarter of this year. The number of foreign tourists who visited Korea in the first quarter reached 4.76 million, marking the highest figure ever recorded for the quarter—a 23 percent increase from the same period last year. The Ministry of Culture, Sports and Tourism attributed the surge to the global popularity of Korean culture. Last month's BTS concert at Gwanghwamun Plaza is believed to have played a significant role. The phenomenon of Korean culture functioning as a driving force for Korea's tourism sector has become increasingly evident in recent years. According to a 2024 survey by the Korea Culture and Tourism Institute, foreign tourists cited \"Korean Wave content\" as the top reason for their interest in Korea, followed by \"Korean traditional culture\" in second place.\n\nEncouraging is the fact that this interest is expanding beyond Seoul to provincial regions rich in diverse traditional culture. According to ministry data, foreign tourists arriving at provincial airports in the first quarter surged 50 percent year-on-year. Many of those using provincial airports have begun turning their attention to regional tourism. The regional visitation rate among foreign tourists who visited Korea in the first quarter reached 34.5 percent, up 3 percentage points from the previous year, while the duration of regional stays and credit card spending within regions jumped 36 percent and 27 percent respectively. While it may be premature to say that the nature of foreign tourism to Korea has fundamentally shifted, the fact that foreigners are venturing into regions, staying longer and spending more is certainly encouraging.\n\nWhen President Lee Jae-myung mentioned at a cabinet meeting on the 14th coordinating local residents, small business owners and tourism activists while having government agencies support such efforts, he appears to have been seeking to nurture this trend. Accordingly, the Ministry of the Interior and Safety has proposed establishing public-private tourism councils at the city, county and district levels, while the Culture Ministry has expressed its commitment to supporting regional tourism activists. The direction of public-private cooperation to actively utilize private sector ideas is sound. However, for results to follow, local government efficiency must be backed in areas such as transportation, infrastructure and regulations, and political considerations that hinder effective decision-making must be excluded. Tourism is one of the precious solutions that can help alleviate regional depopulation and the polarization between Seoul and non-Seoul areas—one of Korea's most urgent challenges today. The opportunity created by the surge in Korean tourism driven by Korean culture must be properly seized.",
      "perspective": "성공의 지역 분배 재촉"
